fields.title: Inchcape 1
fields.info:
Typical NDL time is 18 minutes (i.e., total time on the wreck is about 12-15 mins). Divers are required to have their Advanced OW certification. As this is a deep dive, remember to check your air and NDL more often.

Descend following the line through a shoal of feeding Mackerel to the bow of this purpose sunk wreck.  The wreck was donated by Inchcape Shipping Services in 2001 and is approximately 20m long and 6m wide. It rests upright sitting perfectly on its keel.  

Marine life is everywhere.  Beautiful yellow soft coral greets you as you reach the wreck and small colorful fish dart in and out as you swim over. Off to the side are large shoals of Snapper and along the deck are Lionfish, Scorpionfish, Kingfish, Grouper, Angelfish, Arabian Boxfish, Butterflyfish, several Giant Pufferfish, Moray Eel and several types of Nudibranch.  If you are really lucky, you may find Seahorse and Frogfish.  Along the sides, you will find Nudibranch and other small interesting creatures. A dive light is very helpful for this!

But the main attraction at this site is the two resident Honeycomb Moray Eels!  They are usually found on the deck at the edge near the soft coral, in one of the tires attached to the side, or in the portholes.

If you have your Wreck Specialty certification and excellent buoyancy control, you can choose to enter the wreck at the start of the dive. You must have a dive light for this. Communicate and plan this with your buddy before the dive! Penetrating the wreck takes you 1-2m deeper than the deck and will reduce your overall NDL time.

Be back on the ascent line with 3-5 minutes NDL or 70 Bar, whichever comes first, complete your safety stop, and you’re back in the boat for a nice long surface interval as you travel to our next dive site!

Note: Using regular air you will typically have between 16-18 minutes of NDL on the deck of the wreck.  Those with average air consumption rates will find that they will be at about 70-100 bar with 5 minutes NDL. Using Nitrox can extend your NDL time on this dive if you are good with air consumption or are on Sidemount! If you are Enriched Air specialty certified, you may request Nitrox when you pre-book.  

Ask us about getting Nitrox certified!  The course takes a half-day including classroom sessions and two dives.  Or, complete the classroom portion online at PADI eLearning, bring us your completion certificate and do the practical hands-on session with us in 30 minutes.  Pre-book with us and order your Nitrox tanks for your dives that day!

fields.seo_keywords: Inchcape One, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Three Rocks
fields.info:
Three rocks is also known by the name of Sharm Rock as the small fishing village located near it is called Al Sharm.

This site is about 100m x 50m and is comprised of a large submerged pinnacle rock cluster with the tips of three protruding from the surface of the water during high tide (you can actually see four tips at low tide and has many valleys and crevices to explore.

Descend following the anchor line on the northeast buoy to about 8m and keep the rocks on your right.  You are met by Grouper, Mackerel, Snapper, and Trumpetfish as you make your way around the back and deepest section.  Along the way you will see beautiful red soft Bear Claw Coral blooming on the rocks…typically, a Moray Eel is resting somewhere in this soft coral!  As you make your way around the back of the deepest part of the site, remember to look up towards the shallower rocks and you will likely spot one of several resident Giant Pufferfish, huge schools of Snapper and Mackerel and if they are there, schools of Barracuda are around as well!   Throughout this section of the site, you can also see Trumpetfish, Bannerfish, Arabian Boxfish, Parrotfish, Butterflyfish, Arabian Boxfish, Red Fanged Triggerfish, Broomtail Wrasse, Angelfish, and the well-camouflaged Cuttlefish.

As you make your way back to the shallower section on the south side you can see Turtle, Surgeonfish, Picasso Triggerfish, Bannerfish, and Batfish.  

In the shallow (northwest) portion of the site is beautiful Table Coral.  You should have about 15 minutes remaining to explore the valleys between the rocks.  Here you can see small schools of Batfish, the lone Barracuda, Turtle, Broomtail Wrasse, Porcupine, and Banded Pufferfish, Bannerfish, Arabian Angelfish and the occasional Torpedo / Electric Ray.

You have the option of making your way back to the ascent line for your safety stop, or just send up your Safety Marker Buoy where you are, complete your safety stop and the boat will come to pick you up!

If this is the second dive of your trip, after entering the boat just keep your gear on because of its only 3 minutes back to the dive shop where you will disembark with your gear and make that short walk to the dive shop to disassemble, rinse and hang up your equipment to dry!
fields.seo_description: Three Rocks | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Also Known As Sharm Rock, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Three Rocks, Sharm Rock, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Artificial Reef
fields.info:
After descending down the anchor line to the sandy bottom you will see sets of tires and concrete domes teaming with Spotted Snapper. Locate and follow the larger rope on the seafloor for about 25m and you are taken to a small fishing boat with resident Batfish, Grouper and if you look closely, you may be lucky enough to see Nudibranch.

Continue on the line past the boat another 10m and you’ll see a large group of concrete hollow pyramids (tetrahedron) stacked on top of the other. At the top are shoals of Mackerel and Snapper. Look closely, because the Giant Pufferfish love to use these groups as cover!

As you fin over the top and look down you’ll see Trumpetfish, Grouper, Arabian Angelfish, Batfish, Parrotfish, Lionfish, Anemonefish (Clownfish), Sergeant Major, Cardinalfish, and Bannerfish swimming in and out of the structures. Work your way around the bottom edge and look for Nudibranchs, Moray Eel and Stingray!

Return to the line, complete your safety stop and back in the boat to prepare for your next dive!
fields.seo_description: Artificial Reef | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Artificial Reef, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Dibba Rock
fields.info:
Small rock island approximately 100m x 100m. The captain will drop you in at 4-6m with the current at your back and you will fin keeping the rocks on your left or right depending on whether you enter from the north or south of the island. The shore-side (west) and south side of the island range in depth from 1-4m, while the deepest part is on the east side. Even in the deeper areas, there is a gentle slope of rock that allows you to stay at a shallower depth and still see an abundance of marine life!

In the shallow depths, you can see Parrotfish, Giant Pufferfish, Trumpetfish, Batfish, Broomtail Wrasse, Lionfish, Scorpionfish, Picasso and Red Fanged Triggerfish, Turtle, Sergeant Major, Cardinalfish and Moray Eel. As you fin into the deeper section on the north and east sides you can see these plus you may also find Squid, Cuttlefish and Blacktip Reef Shark, Cowtail Stingray, Eagle Ray and if you are really lucky, the occasional Whaleshark!

Send up your surface marker buoy, complete your surface interval, surface and the boat will come to pick you up!
fields.seo_description: Dibba Rock | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Dibba Rock, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Cauliflower  Reef
fields.info:
You are required to have your Deep Diver Specialty certification for this site. It is on the depths limit for recreational scuba diving. This site is often done during our technical and deep diver training.

Cauliflower reef is located about 500m directly east of Dibba Rock. The captain will use a GPS to locate the site. Once located we will drop down a shot line to use as a reference during our descent.

As you descend to 40m you will be met with a sandy bottom and scattered large teddy bear Cauliflower corals. After about an 8min bottom time for recreational divers or an extended bottom time for technical divers, you will start your ascent. At about 15m you will send up your SMB to mark your position. The captain will then pick you up by boat.
fields.seo_description: Cauliflower Reef | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Cauliflower Reef, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Snoopy Island
fields.info:
Find a buddy, put on your gear, walk 40m and you are diving! Snoopy Island is a great shore dive.  It is perfect for day and night dives!

A small rock island about 120m x 80m, Snoopy Island is named for the three sections of rock rising up to create a profile of feet, belly, and nose similar to the iconic image of Snoopy©️ sleeping on top of his doghouse!

Enter from the shore, surface swim about 200m to the last buoy and drop down to 4-5m at the southwest corner.  Look for the resident Torpedo / Electric Ray buried in the sand near the buoy line anchor.  Keep the rocks on your left as you glide over Grouper resting on the rocks and coral clusters … along the rocks and coral, you can see Moray Eel, Trumpetfish, Arabian Boxfish, Parrotfish, Butterflyfish, Arabian Boxfish, Sergeant Major, Cardinalfish, Snapper, Picasso and Red Fanged Triggerfish, Broomtail Wrasse, Surgeonfish, Angelfish, Turtle, Nudibranch, and Cuttlefish. 

During a night dive, look for red Reef Octopus along this section!

Just before you make your left turn to reach the backside of the island you are met by a large shoal of Mackerel … sometimes so thick it nearly blocks out the sun!  Gently glide through and they will encircle you.  Buddies stay close to each other because you can lose sight of each other. You may also see Barracuda or Queenfish looking for lunch … and the Mackerel are on the menu!

Along the back and deepest part (east side) of the island, you may find Ray, Squid, Giant Pufferfish, Turtle and Blacktip Reef Shark. 

On the northeast side, the depth is 3-4m and this is the location of the larger Boulder and Brain Coral clusters.  In the late afternoon, it is common to find a resting Turtle or two at the base of these clusters.  

You’ve already completed your safety stop, so just surface and then surface swim back to shore.  If you are REALLY good on air consumption and have the time, you could reverse the dive with the rocks now on your right, return to the location where you started, ascend and then surface swim to shore!  That’s about a 70-minute dive!
fields.seo_description: Snoopy Island | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive!
fields.seo_keywords: Snoopy Island, Dive Snoopy Island, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Snoopy Deep Reef
fields.info:
This site requires an Advanced certification level. It is located about 500m directly east of Snoopy Island. The site has a bottom topography of flatbed rock and sandy patches. To attract fish, tires and rope have been laid on the seafloor.

An accident with a small diving boat left the boat unusable. The boat was towed out to the site, the boat and trailer were purposefully sunk to attract fish to the site. There is no mooring line on the site. To protect the delicate soft coral below we do not throw anchor or a shot line.

You will kit up on the boat and backward roll into the water. Your dive guide will lead you on a descent without a reference line. Once you reach the bottom at about 24m you will notice an abundance of large tree corals. You will explore the small dive boat and trailer. You can expect to spot the usual reef creatures on this site such as Box Fish, Angel Fish, Snapper and Broomtail Wrasse. Moray eels like to hide in the rocky crevices and Sea Horses perch on the ropes attached to the tires.

After about a 27-minute bottom time or if you reach 60 bar your dive guide will lead you on your ascent and send an SMB to mark your location to the boat captain. You will then hop back on the boat and prepare for your second dive or come into shore.
fields.seo_description: Snoopy Deep Reef | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive!
fields.seo_keywords: Snoopy Deep Reef, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Coral Gardens
fields.info:
This site is a beautiful reef just outside of the Khor Fakkhan port. The island nearby is called Shark Island. 

There is an abundance of hard corals, the island has a gradual slope towards a sandy bottom. After entering the water you will head down to about 14m which will be at the contour of sand and rocky slope. 

Heading towards the port you will notice abundant marine life in between all the corals. Once you have reached low on air or time of about 40min, the dive guide will head to the shallow water in a protected bay.

This bay is about 3m -5m deep. It is protected from any incoming bad weather. This has allowed corals to form over many years, the tables corals on this site are the largest in the region. It is a nursery for juvenile reef fish.

Once the dive is over you will be able to snorkel back to the boat or the boat captain will collect you once all the divers are ready!
fields.seo_description: Coral Gardens | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Coral Gardens, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Shark Island
fields.info:
This site is on the eastern end of Shark Island. It offers a good chance of seeing sharks. The wall slopes off quite quickly and ends on the sandy bottom around 22m deep.

The site is in close proximity to Anemone Gardens which may be another option if you would like to do that dive site. 

Shark Island has abundant marine life and is a wonderful site to dive with your buddies
fields.seo_description: Shark Island | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Shark Island, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Hole in The Wall
fields.info:
The site is a submerged outcrop of the mountain running just along the shoreline.  The two largest formations breach the water surface and gently slope away from the pinnacle as you get deeper. Similar to Three Rocks, the underwater rock formations have many small valleys and crevices to explore.  Along the edges at the bottom in the sand are many large boulders where you may find the resting Cowtail Ray, Blackspotted / Marbled Ray, Whiptail Ray, and Turtle.  A bit further out in the sand you may be lucky enough to find a curious and shy Jawfish with his eyes just above the edge of his hole in the seafloor and his mouth full of eggs!  Throughout the site, you may see Trumpetfish, Bannerfish, Arabian Boxfish, Parrotfish, Butterflyfish, Arabian Boxfish, Red Fanged Triggerfish, Broomtail Wrasse, Angelfish, Blenny, Goby, Cleaner Wrasse, Moray Eel and the well-camouflaged Cuttlefish.

The dive is named for a 15m long swim-through.  This natural tunnel is located nearer the shoreline and has an average width of 2m and 1m height.  The northwest entrance is approximately 3m deep and the southeast entrance is 7m.  It has a sandy bottom, so frog/flutter kick should be used to avoid stirring up the silt and allow the next person to enjoy the same view as you. There is usually a small school of Silver Sweeper hanging out in the widest part (3m) near the east side. If you have a dive light (or if the sun is bright and visibility good) look slightly upwards and you may see several Lobsters hiding in crevices!

Depending on visibility and time of day (sunlight), it can be challenging to find if you are unfamiliar with the site.  So, stay with your guide at least until he or she takes you through and then you can explore the site on your own if you want (let your dive guide know pre-dive that this is your plan).

For those that opt to explore on their own, the captain will get you close to the main pinnacle on the southwest section of the site. Descend down 6-7m keeping the rocks on your right and fin towards the deeper portion of the site (east) then continue until a depth of about 5-6m and come to a shallow wall directly in front of you.  Slight turn left keeping the rocks on your right, and you will soon see a sand pathway between the two shallow walls … continue past this and the very next sand pathway on your right will take you to the east entrance of Hole in the Wall.  The sand path is about 15m long and depending on visibility and time of day, the hole may not be visible until you are within a few meters … it will just look like a wall.  But as soon as you are close enough you will see the entrance and the light shining in through the other side! When you exit you are immersed in sunlight and surrounded by Brain Coral, Staghorn Coral, and Table Coral as well as the accompanying reef fish!  Explore this area for the remaining 10 minutes, make your way back to the anchor line or surface and its a one minute surface swim back to the boat!
fields.seo_description: Hole In The Wall | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Hole In The Wall, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Inchape 2
fields.info:
Typical NDL time is 36 minutes (i.e., total time on the wreck is about 28-33 mins) or 70 Bar back on the ascent line, whichever comes first.

Descend following the line through a shoal of feeding Mackerel to the bow of this purpose sunk wreck.  The wreck was donated by Inchcape Shipping Services in 2002. The wreck is nearly identical to Inchcape 1, but slightly longer (25m) and also rests upright sitting perfectly on his keel.

Off to the side are large shoals of Snapper and along the deck are three huge resident  Lionfish.  Also on the deck are Scorpionfish, Grouper, Angelfish, Arabian Boxfish, Moray Eel, Butterflyfish, several Giant Pufferfish and several types of Nudibranch.  Along the sides and the deck of the vessel, you will find Nudibranch and other small interesting creatures. A dive light is very helpful for this!  Around the edges in the sand, you might find a large resting Stingray

If you have your Wreck Specialty certification and excellent buoyancy control, you can choose to enter the wreck at the start of the dive. You must have a dive light for this. Communicate and plan this with your buddy before the dive! Penetrating the wreck will reduce your remaining NDL time… so there is a trade-off.

Be back on the ascent line with 3-5 minutes NDL or 70 Bar, whichever comes first, complete your safety stop and you’re back in the boat for your surface interval as you travel to the next dive site!
fields.seo_description: Inchcape Two | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Ship Wreck, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Inchcape Two, Ship Wreck, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Martini Rock
fields.info:
Named after its shape, this rock is a haven for marine life. The pinnacle starts at 5m and slopes off all the way down to 20m

There is an abundance of soft corals on this site. It is one of our furthest dive sites.

Once entering the water you will follow the buoy line down to the sandy bottom at around 12m. Then head in a westerly direction towards deeper water. Once at the bottom of the rock, start your ascent around the other side off the rock.

Many Rays and chances of Whale-Sharks exist at this site. You and your buddy will be able to follow the rock all the way up to your safety stop. You can do your safety stop at the top of the rock allowing you to see all the marine life.

Once completed the dive boat will collect you.
fields.seo_description: Martini Rock | Explore Fujairah Dive Sites | Discover This Beautiful Dive Site, Abundant Marine Life And Beautiful Corals, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Martini Rock, Fujairah Dive Sites

fields.title: Boat Dive
fields.description:
Boat diving in Fujairah offers the best diving in the UAE, from amazing shipwrecks to beautiful coral reefs. We know the best sites to dive in Fujairah, there is an abundance of marine life in the area, Dolphins, Whalesharks, various species of turtle and many Indo-Pacific reef fish. The area offers dive sites for all certification and comfort levels. 

All of our dive sites are no more than a short boat trip away, we run two trips per day, please check out our dive sites page for a full list of dive sites. Shark Island in Fujairah, is one of the many beautiful sites we have. If you would like to visit the famous Snoopy Island you can kit up at the centre and head out from the shore. Visit our shore diving page for more info about shore diving around Snoopy Island. 

Our dive centre has a full range of diving equipment which can be hired, we also offer equipment for sale in our showroom.
fields.schedule:
We run two dive trips from the boat per day, our boat is fully kitted for diving with spare equipment if needed, emergency equipment and tank racks. 

Our boats accommodate a maximum of 13 divers per trip. The trips include two dives at two different dive sites. Checkout our diving schedule below.
fields.seo_description: Fujairah Boat Diving | Discover | PADI 5 Star IDC Resort | Daily Boat Diving Trips To Any Of Our Awesome Dive Sites, Sign Up For Your Next Dive Today!
fields.seo_keywords: Boat Diving, Dive Trip, Boat Dive, Dive Fujairah, Fujairah Boat Dive Trip

fields.title: Shore Dive
fields.description:
Diving Snoopy Island is a fun and easy dive. The site is located within a marine national park which means no fishing is allowed around the island, because of this the marine life is flourishing. A diver can spot Blacktip reef sharks, resident Green turtles and an abundance of reef fish. There are beautiful corals that rise up to 2m beneath the surface of the water.

Bring your own equipment or rent equipment from us, we will give you a short dive briefing of the site, we will explain where the best areas are and what our dive procedures are, you and your buddy can then head out and explore the beauty of Snoopy Island.

Once you have completed your dive we have rinse tanks and showers at our facility. You can then sit back and relax with a cup of tea or coffee while you take in the beautiful scenery.
fields.schedule:
Shore diving can be done at any time during the day. We also offer night dives around Snoopy Island. Please check out the price list for prices on night diving. Our shore dives expect that you will have your own buddy to dive around Snoopy Island. 

Let us know if you would like a dive guide to dive around Snoopy Island with you. There are so many beautiful animals around Snoopy Island. Prices include access to the hotel as well as full-service dive facilities, showers, equipment rinse areas, and a classroom.

Your instructor will lead you through this course, with the help of a video and textbook to guide you through your knowledge development in the classroom.

fields.description: The PADI Deep Diver course will extend your depth range to 40m. There are many reasons divers choose to dive deep: a wreck you want to explore or the lure of a deep wall dive. This course will give you the confidence to slowly and responsibly extend your depth range with the use of deep diving equipment, procedures and techniques. During the course you will learn to think like a Deep Diver, plan your gas supply and manage gas narcosis.

fields.title: Wreck Diver
fields.description: Welcome to the PADI Wreck Diver specialty course. Who is she and how did she get there? Shipwrecks can be very intriguing and can have significant historical relevance. During this course, you will learn how to navigate shipwrecks, prevent siltation and navigate your way safely into and out of wrecks.

fields.title: Night Diver
fields.description: Welcome to the PADI Night Diver Specialty course. Night diving can feel like a stressful and daunting experience. It is the exact opposite once you get in the water. Night diving is more relaxing than day diving. You are exposed to a whole new array of underwater creatures. Crabs, Lobsters and Moray Eels all come out to play at night. All the coral polyps will open during the night to feed on passing nutrients in the water. During the night diver course, you will learn how to use an underwater light and how to navigate at night.

fields.title: Search and Recovery
fields.description: Welcome to the PADI Search and Recovery specialty course. Have you ever lost a weight belt or your sunglasses off the side of the boat? This is an excellent course to teach you many different search patterns and object lifting techniques. During the course, you will practice search patterns using a compass and mark off search areas using buoys. You will also learn to use a lift bag to bring objects to the surface.

This course will teach you the best settings and scenery to make your pictures look great. Our experienced instructors will explain the best way to configure your camera to set for optimum exposure and lighting. During the course you will learn the use of extra lighting and flashes. You will cover portrait, landscape and macro photography.

fields.title: Peak Performance Buoyancy
fields.description: Welcome to the PADI Peak Performance Buoyancy specialty course. Buoyancy is the skill most used during your dives and having excellent buoyancy is often overlooked and undervalued. In today’s diving world, it is essential not only to improve your diving experience but also to protect the environment. During the course, you will learn different weighting methods and distribution and you will practice hovering and different kicking techniques. By the end of the course, you will be in the perfect horizontal diving position with the optimum amount of weight.

fields.title: Fish Identification
fields.description: Welcome to the PADI Fish Identification Specialty course. What was that fish with the big tail and orange stripes? During this course, you will learn not only how to identify single fish species but also start learning about fish families, which will make identifying them that much easier. This is a fun course where you will learn all about fish species in the region and around the world. It is very informative and will add a new dimension to your diving experiences.

Using nitrox is extremely popular on live-aboard dive trips and it is very beneficial if you are planning on doing multiple dives per day.

fields.title: Tec 40
fields.description: Tec 40 is the first of the PADI TecRec course.It will test your ability as a diver, you will be entering the world of decompression diving. Excellent dive skills, techniques, and procedures are required for technical level courses. During the Tec 40 course, you will be introduced to basic decompression procedures and techniques. You will be introduced to a back-mounted twin set diving configuration. If you are already a Tec Sidemount diver we can do the course in either back mount or sidemount.  The PADI TecRec program is challenging but very rewarding! If you are ready to take the next step, let's get into what the course involves.

fields.title: Pool Info
fields.heading: Pool Dives
fields.text: We have an onsite swimming pool based in Sandy Beach Hotel and Resort. All pool training dives are done in our own swimming pool. The pool is crystal clear throughout the year and has a maximum depth of 2.2m.

fields.title: Ocean Dives
fields.heading: Ocean Dives
fields.text:
Our ocean training dives are split between two different dive types, boat diving, and shore diving. This gives us a unique opportunity, it affords us a varied training experience, building students' confidence with different entry styles and diving techniques.

Our boat dives visit the many dive sites along the coast, all varying in-depth and marine life. The shore dives are done around Snoopy Island which is bursting with corals and marine life. We regularly spot turtles and black-tip reef sharks on Snoopy Island

fields.title: Book Learning
fields.heading: Book Learning
fields.text:
Our classroom is fitted with a TV as well as a whiteboard with all the training materials necessary for effective learning. In the classroom is where most of our theory takes place.

When doing book-based learning, it should be noted that that depending on student progress, an extra day may be added to the duration of the course.

fields.title: E-Learning
fields.heading: PADI E-Learning
fields.text:
PADI e-learning is an effective and time-efficient way to complete your theory. All learning can be done online at your own pace before coming into the dive center to complete your open water training dives.

Follow the link below to sign up for your online learning. If you have any questions or issues during the online learning please don't hesitate to contact us, we will be able to assist.
